default&#xa0;
defaultCase Study default10default: All Schools Programme defaultIn 2012 
defaultThe RFU launched All Schools.  
defaultAll Schools was founded on the principles that ALL schools can play rugby, ALL of t
defaulthe 
defaultchildren in the school can
default play, and rugby has a positive impact on ALL of the school. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe RFU provides tailored support to each school, depending on their needs, challenges and opportunities
default over a three year period
default.  The RFU are therefore pleased that 
defaultmore than half of the schools in Phase 1 opted to have girls-only or mixed sessions in their schoolsdefault.
default&#xa0;
defaultAll Schools is one of seven area areas identified by the RFU to deliver the greatest participation legacy for the game in the lead up to the Rugby World 
defaultCup 2015 and beyond.  The RFU has set up All Schools to 
defaulthelp more state schools that haven’t traditionally played rugbydefault to offer the Game to their students.  We aim to help 400 state secondary schools new to rugby to become self-sufficient rugby playing sc
defaulthools and linked into their local rugby clubs by the 2015 Rugby World Cup.
default&#xa0;defaultSchools have been identified in small clusters, allowing them to play rugby against each other locally.  The schools in Phase 1 2012-13 (100) and Phase 2 2013-14 (an additional 100
default) have been selected on a number of factors including: local rugby club need for young players, proximity to potential RWC2015 venues, and areas of the country that to date haven’t had a large rugby union following.
default&#xa0;
defaultRugby generates whole school improvemen
defaultt and the RFU encourages coaches and teachers to help youngsters understand and practice rugby’s core values – 
defaultTeamwork, Respect, Enjoyment, Discipline, defaultSportsmanshipdefault.  Teachers from schools which have participated in Year 1 have reported improving behavio
defaultur, enhanced learning and increasing self-esteem amongst students.  
default&#xa0;
defaultCanterbury, the kit partner of England Rugby, is the Official Partner of All Schools.  Each school taking part in the programme is given the opportunity to attend a Canterbury kit design
default workshop.  The students design their own team rugby shirt, whilst learning about the core values of rugby, the pride associated with the shirt and the importance of colours, logos and emblems, which is made up and presented to the schools at Twickenham.
